<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="280" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[801,1452,439,911]" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis box="[839,895,440,463]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Trees</emphasis>
. Indument comprising short, straight, appressed trichomes; glandular scales absent; buds not “varnished”. 
<emphasis box="[801,870,504,527]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Leaves</emphasis>
alternate, 1–4-jugate; leaflets opposite to subopposite, subsessile to petiolulate, margin entire. Inflorescences axillary or pseudo-terminal. 
<emphasis box="[1067,1148,567,591]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Flowers</emphasis>
actinomorphic, functionally unisexual; calyx 5-dentate, teeth equal; petals 5, with a distinct claw, scales minute, petal margin with minute enations; disc more or less distinctly five-lobed, rim subpilose; stamens (6–)8(– 10), anthers basifixed; ovary (2 –)3-locular. 
<emphasis box="[1374,1431,696,719]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Fruit</emphasis>
a capsule, with 1 or 2 well developed lobes, dehiscence loculicidal, central axis distinctly thickened, glabrous to puberulous and rugose to verrucose outside, pilose inside, calyx persistent; seed ellipsoid, sarcotesta covering all or sometimes only half of the seed (
<taxonomicName box="[902,1060,855,879]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Neoarytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="neoebudensis">
<emphasis box="[902,1060,855,879]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">N. neoebudensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), fleshy-membranaceous, comprising a single layer. Radicle bearing trichomes, at least basally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="280" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[801,1451,951,1039]" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis box="[839,972,951,975]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Distribution</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName box="[1008,1123,952,975]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Neoarytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1008,1123,952,975]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Neoarytera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises four species, three endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[942,1124,983,1007]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
and one occurring on both 
<collectingCountry box="[801,968,1015,1039]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1021,1110,1015,1038]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1125,1191,1015,1039]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[136,167,964,983]" captionTargetBox="[136,786,276,941]" captionTargetId="graphics-613@10.[-236,786,191,1015]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 4. – Distribution map of Lepidocupania Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry (black line) and Neoarytera Callm., Buerki, Munzinger &amp; Lowry (white line) in the southern Pacific. [Oceania Region Map by Vemaps.com]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5724907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5724907/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="280" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[801,1454,1079,1487]" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis box="[839,894,1080,1103]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Notes</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName box="[925,1035,1080,1103]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Neoarytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[925,1035,1080,1103]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Neoarytera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the distinctly thickened central axis of its fruit (vs. not thickened in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", TURNER" authorityYear="1995" box="[1328,1405,1111,1134]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Arytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1328,1405,1111,1134]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Arytera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", ADEMA" authorityYear="1991" box="[801,920,1143,1166]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Cupaniopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,920,1143,1166]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Cupaniopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), petal scales comprising minute enations (vs. scales adnate to the margins of the petals or free from the petals in the other two genera), and its 3-, rarely 2-locular ovary and fruit (vs. ovary and fruit 2- or 3-locular in the two other genera). 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", TURNER" authorityYear="1995" box="[801,878,1271,1294]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Arytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,878,1271,1294]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Arytera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as re-circumscribed here, can easily be distinguished by its 2-layered sarcotesta (vs. single-layer in 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", ADEMA" authorityYear="1991" box="[1282,1405,1303,1326]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Cupaniopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1282,1405,1303,1326]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Cupaniopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[801,908,1336,1359]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Neoarytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,908,1336,1359]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Neoarytera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="TURNER, H." box="[931,1111,1335,1359]" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" refId="ref12575" refString="TURNER, H. (1995). Cladistic and biogeographic analyses of Arytera Blume and Mischarytera gen. nov. (Sapindaceae) with notes on methodology and a full taxonomic revision. Blumea, Suppl. 9." type="book" year="1995">TURNER, 1995: 72</bibRefCitation>
). Finally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", ADEMA" authorityYear="1991" box="[1207,1325,1335,1358]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Cupaniopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1207,1325,1335,1358]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Cupaniopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", TURNER" authorityYear="1995" box="[801,876,1367,1390]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Arytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,876,1367,1390]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Arytera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[927,1036,1368,1391]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Neoarytera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[927,1036,1368,1391]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="280">Neoarytera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having free or nearly free calyx lobes, which are usually 2-seriate, orbicular, elliptic or obovate, and concave (vs. calyx shortly cupular, the lobes toothed or divided, and usually ovate in the other two genera) (
<bibRefCitation author="REYNOLDS, S. T." box="[1256,1443,1463,1487]" pageId="11" pageNumber="280" pagination="153 - 189" refId="ref12468" refString="REYNOLDS, S. T. (1985 a). Notes on Sapindaceae IV. Austrobaileya 2: 153 - 189." type="journal article" year="1985">REYNOLDS, 1985a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
